<h1 id="managed-certificates">Managed certificates</h1>
<p>Microsoft documentation for managed certs are specific to each product, here&rsquo;s the <a href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/frontdoor/front-door-custom-domain-https#option-1-default-use-a-certificate-managed-by-front-door">FrontDoor documentation</a>.</p>
<h4 id="when-to-use-managed-certificates">When to use Managed Certificates</h4>
<p>If you are using one of the following services:
- Frontdoor
- CDN
- App Service</p>
<h4 id="frontdoor-managed-certificate-limitations">FrontDoor managed certificate limitations</h4>
<p><em>Other services may have these limitations too, not verified</em></p>

<ul>
<li><a href="https://www.quora.com/What-is-an-apex-domain">Apex domains</a> do not work with managed certificates, e.g. <code>hmcts-access.service.gov.uk</code></li>
<li>Domains using <a href="https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/frontdoor/front-door-custom-domain#map-the-temporary-afdverify-subdomain">afdverify</a> only and not direct validation do not work</li>
</ul>
<p>You should use <a href="letsencrypt.md">Letâ€™s encrypt certificates</a> in the above scenarios.</p>
